The move comes at a time when Coca-Cola is building its non-carbonated drinks portfolio. BENGALURU - Coca-Cola Co said Muhtar Kent would step aside as chief executive on 1 May after about nine years at the helm, and be replaced by Chief Operating Officer James Quincey.Kent, 64, will continue as chairperson, the company said.Quincey, 51, joined Coca-Cola in 1996 and became chief operating officer in August 2015.His appointment as CEO was given a vote of confidence by Warren Buffett, CEO of Berkshire Hathaway Inc, which is Coca-Cola's largest shareholder. I know James and like him, and believe the company has made a smart investment in its future with his selection, Buffett said in a statement.The move comes at a time when Coca-Cola is building its non-carbonated drinks portfolio, cutting costs by selling its bottling operations and stepping up efforts to reduce sugar in its beverages to counter slowing sales.Coca-Cola still gets about 70% of its volume sales from fizzy drinks.The company's shares were up 1.4% at $41.55 in premarket trading.